{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9933b422-a112-4c68-a328-f560676b44f4","content":"There are no files in the working directory, so this is a general guidance question. Here's how to do it:\n\n### 1. Add `x:DataType` to enable compiled bindings\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n             xmlns:vm=\"clr-namespace:YourApp.ViewModels\"\n             x:Class=\"YourApp.Views.SettingsPage\"\n             x:DataType=\"vm:SettingsViewModel\">\n\n    <VerticalStackLayout Padding=\"20\" Spacing=\"15\">\n\n        <Picker Title=\"Theme\"\n                SelectedItem=\"{Binding Theme}\" />\n\n        <HorizontalStackLayout Spacing=\"10\">\n            <Label Text=\"Notifications\" VerticalOptions=\"Center\" />\n            <Switch IsToggled=\"{Binding NotificationsEnabled}\" />\n        </HorizontalStackLayout>\n\n        <HorizontalStackLayout Spacing=\"10\">\n            <Label Text=\"Font Size\" VerticalOptions=\"Center\" />\n            <Stepper Value=\"{Binding FontSize}\" Minimum=\"8\" Maximum=\"36\" Increment=\"1\" />\n            <Label Text=\"{Binding FontSize, StringFormat='{0}pt'}\" />\n        </HorizontalStackLayout>\n\n    </VerticalStackLayout>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nThe key change is **`x:DataType=\"vm:SettingsViewModel\"`** on the `ContentPage`. This tells the XAML compiler the expected type for all `{Binding}` expressions in scope.\n\n### 2. Catch binding errors at build time\n\n**a) Enable strict mode in your `.csproj`:**\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n    <!-- Treat binding warnings as errors -->\n    <WarningsAsErrors>$(WarningsAsErrors);XC0045</WarningsAsErrors>\n    <!-- Alternatively, make ALL warnings errors: -->\n    <!-- <TreatWarningsAsErrors>true</TreatWarningsAsErrors> -->\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n`XC0045` is the diagnostic for compiled-binding mismatches (property not found on the declared type).\n\n**b) What this catches:** If you typo a property name (e.g., `{Binding Theeme}`), the build will now **fail** instead of silently returning nothing at runtime.\n\n### 3. Scoped `x:DataType` for nested types\n\nIf a child element binds to a different type (e.g., inside a `CollectionView.ItemTemplate`), set `x:DataType` on that subtree:\n\n```xml\n<CollectionView.ItemTemplate>\n    <DataTemplate x:DataType=\"model:SettingItem\">\n        <Label Text=\"{Binding Name}\" />\n    </DataTemplate>\n</CollectionView.ItemTemplate>\n```\n\n### Summary\n\n| Step | What it does |\n|---|---|\n| `x:DataType=\"...\"` | Resolves bindings at compile time |\n| `XC0045` as error | Fails the build on bad bindings |\n| Scoped `x:DataType` | Handles different types in subtrees |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4833d22d-415a-404c-a262-0c98e781dbde","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"There are no files in the directory. The user is asking a general question about converting a .NET MAUI page to use compiled bindings. I should provide a clear, helpful answer explaining the conversion and how to catch binding errors at build time, without needing actual files to modify.","outputTokens":841,"requestId":"DC06:19AB05:8E034:B0B13:69F54A32"},"id":"8868d020-4dd6-4578-a333-2844e997d8eb","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:50:11.226Z","parentId":"458228a6-8e18-41b1-aaf3-71c495df6dd9"}
